n ceiling of 21 million barrels a day to begin on Oct. 1and run through the end of the year.   But an evening meeting where OPEC delegates were expected toformalize the plan was abruptly postponed, surprising someministers who had already gathered. Officials said there werelast-minute snags in negotiations.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. stock shothigher as the movie and television programmer said it was in activediscussions about selling the company, triggering speculation thatthe suitor was Japan's Sony Corp.   Columbia Pictures and Sony, which previously had indicated aninterest in buying a movie studio, each declined to comment Mondayon a report that the electronics giant had offered to buy Columbia.   Coca-Cola Co., the Atlanta-based soft drink maker that owns 49percent of Columbia's stock, said it was aware Columbia was indiscussions and that it would consider whatever recommendation maybe made.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   RJR Nabisco Inc. said it had made the last majorasset sale under a $5.5 billion divestiture plan as an investorgroup led by Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. agreed to buy its Del Monte cannedfood business for $1.48 billion.   Del Monte's senior management, Citicorp Capital Investors Ltd.and Kikkoman Corp. also are members of the investor group.   RJR Nabisco said Monday that proceeds from the sale will bringto approximately $4.9 billion the amount of money it has earnedfrom its divestiture program.</TEXT><DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Coors Brewing Co. offered $425 million tobuy Stroh Brewing Co., a move analysts said effectively creates a``Big Three'' group of dominant U.S. breweries.   The purchase price announced Monday includes cash plusassumption of long-term debt and certain other liabilities. Thetransaction is subject to a definitive agreement and approval bythe boards of directors of both companies and government regulators.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Aviation Administration said ithas tightened security standards since the December bombing of PanAm Flight 103, but a General Accounting Office investigation saidthe FAA doesn't know if airlines are meeting the standards.   The GAO report, the details of which are being kept secret byCongress, was summarized by Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., at ahearing Monday of her House Government Operations subcommittee ongovernment activities and transportation.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government is asking United Airlines todisclose how much foreign influence over the airline a plannedemployee-management takeover would allow, officials said.   The inquiry came as The Wall Street Journal reported Monday thatTransportation Secretary Samuel Skinner had asked NorthwestAirlines' new principal owner, Alfred Checchi, to cut by $225million the $400 million investment made in NWA Inc., the airline'sparent corporation, by KLM Royal Dutch Airlines.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market sustained a broad loss Monday in the slowesttrading in more than 2{ months. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials dropped 22.42 points to a five-week low of 2,659.19.   Bond prices fell sharply as the dollar plummeted in foreignexchange due to dollar-selling by the central banks of severalindustrial nations. Interest rates rose.   Cotton futures prices made strong gains on the New York CottonExchange; copper futures fell; gold and platinum rose; energyfutures advanced; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock andmeat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>